<TEXT>
the judge in the irancontra conspiracy case 
is setting up procedures for dealing with classified documents in 
an apparent effort to bring fired white house aide oliver l north 
to trial by fall 
us district judge gerhard a gesell ordered north to identify 
by july 11 which secret government documents the retired marine 
lieutenant colonel wants to disclose in court to rebut charges that 
he illegally diverted iranian armssale profits to the nicaraguan 
rebels 
in a ruling on wednesday gesell said that both the public and 
prosecutors would be barred from a july 14 hearing to determine if 
any of the documents are relevant to the case against north 
the judge also rejected a defense motion to declare the 
classified information procedures act unconstitutional as it 
applied to the case of north former national security adviser john 
m poindexter and arms dealers albert hakim and richard v secord 
the four defendants whom gesell has said must be tried 
separately contended that the law unfairly required them to tell 
the prosecution what documents they intended to make public before 
the trials 
such disclosures would give independent counsel lawrence e 
walsh an unfair tactical advantage the defense said 
acknowledging the problem gesell said strict application of 
the statute to this proceeding would not only be difficult but 
impossible to accomplish consistent with a fair and expeditious 
resolution of this case 
gesell noted that the large volume of classified documents 
collected by walshs investigation about 200000 pages by the 
latest count posed unique problems for a trial judge that were 
probably not envisioned when congress passed the classified 
information statute in 1980 
some of the witnesses and defendants particularly north 
operated from secure locations in the white house with full access 
to the most sensitive information and most critical national 
security intelligence methods and sources available to the 
government gesell said 
this information and even some methods and sources are 
inextricably enmeshed in the events challenged by the indictment 
he added 
but in enacting the law congress gave trial judges authority 
to fashion creative and fair solutions to difficult problems 
posed by such sensitive information gesell said 
lawmakers emphasized that the court should not undertake to 
balance the national security interests of the government against 
the rights of the defendant but rather that in the end remedies and 
sanctions against the government must be designed to make the 
defendant whole again 
while afforded this leeway the court is unable to determine 
definitively at this stage whether or not the classified document 
problems presented by this case can be resolved gesell said in 
the 16page opinion 
it proposes to make the effort but the complexity of the 
situation defies obvious answers final ruling on the defense 
motion must await further developments 
gesell said that he would exclude walsh from discussions of 
whether classified documents that north proposes to disclose are 
relevant to the case gesell will decide which documents are 
relevant and admissible as evidence 
only after an interdepartmental task force has identified 
relevant documents that pose national security problems will walsh 
be included in the process of how to present them in court gesell 
said 
indicating a desire to move the case to trial gesell gave the 
government secrecy experts until aug 1 to complete their review of 
the documents identified by north 
the task force composed of representatives of various 
government intelligence agencies is reviewing the documents that 
walsh collected during his investigation from the cia the fbi the 
national security council the state department and the defense 
department 
after the panels task is completed gesell said he would 
convene closed hearings to determine how to edit out portions of 
documents that cannot be declassified 
under the law the court has the power to order deletions of 
sensitive material or to substitute a statement of facts that the 
document would prove if it were shown to the jury 
if a sufficient number of documents cannot be disclosed in any 
fashion the court can dismiss charges against a defendant on the 
ground he could not get a fair trial 
gesells ruling follows his determination last week that walshs 
investigation was not tainted by impermissible use of the testimony 
that north poindexter and hakim gave to congress last year under 
limited grants of immunity from prosecution 
both decisions indicate that gesell has determined that barring 
unforeseen problems created by classified documents the case can 
move ahead to trial by september 
in a statement walsh said we appreciate the courts prompt 
ruling on the constitutionality of the classified information 
procedures act as it applies to this case and we are prepared to 
move forward as directed by the court 
