legislation requiring the nations railroad 
workers to undergo random drug testing has begun to make progress 
in the electionyear conscious house 
the house transportation tourism and hazardous materials 
subcommittee voted 130 on wednesday to send the measure to the 
full energy and commerce committee the committees chairman rep 
john dingell dmich who has been reluctant to support the 
measure is now expected to give the legislation prompt 
consideration 
i expect it to be called up right away said rep thomas a 
luken dohio the subcommittee chairman after his panel approved 
the bill 
luken cosponsored the measure with rep bob whittaker of 
kansas the subcommittees ranking republican who said public 
support for ridding drug and alcohol abuse from the transportation 
industry is simply overwhelming 
there has been growing support in congress for drug testing 
legislation since jan 4 1987 when an amtrak passenger train and 
three conrail locomotives collided in chase md the crash killed 
16 people and injured 175 others and two conrail crewmen have 
admitted to having smoked marijuana shortly before the disaster 
railroad labor officials have opposed proposals for random 
testing saying that the procedures would violate the privacy of 
the workers and unfairly threaten their careers because of the risk 
of inaccurate laboratory analysis 
that opposition has been diminishing however as electionyear 
pressures have increased for lawmakers to do something about drug 
abuse in addition the federal railroad administration proposed 
drug testing rules for railroad workers on may 5 that many union 
leaders consider harsher than the legislation 
the bill would require not only random testing which supporters 
say would deter alcohol and drug abuse but testing after 
accidents before hiring for reasonable cause and as a part of 
annual physical examinations 
workers who test positive would be given a second more 
sophisticated test to confirm the results if they test positive 
again they would be suspended without pay and required to complete 
rehabilitation programs to keep their jobs employees who refuse to 
take tests would risk being fired 
procedures would be established to certify the laboratories 
being used and to protect workers against harassment 
luken who had long expressed fears about erroneous test 
results resisted introducing legislation until june 3 that was 
five weeks after dr roger horn of hunt valley md whose daughter 
ceres 16 was killed in the chase crash visited newspapers and 
television and radio stations in lukens cincinnati district to 
argue that random testing was needed 
the senate has already approved legislation that would require 
random drug and alcohol testing for railroad airline and trucking 
industry workers 
rail workers involved in accidents are already subject to drug 
and alcohol tests but those rules are being challenged in court 
