<DOCNO> AP880623-0082 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
school systems comprised of innercity 
neighborhoods and suburbs that bus students for racial balance are 
the most successful at maintaining integrated schools a study 
concludes 
the finding is one of several contained in a report released 
wednesday at the annual meeting of the national school boards 
association 
that was one of the more interesting findings given the 
fierce battling that goes on over desegregation said political 
scientist gary orfield of the university of chicago the 
perception is often that reassigning students to other 
neighborhoods encourages white flight 
but the places that have been most successful nashville las 
vegas nev most every big city in florida except miami have 
been those where the city and suburbs are in the same district and 
you can implement a districtwide desegregation plan orfield said 
researchers led by orfield and political scientist franklin 
monfort of the university of wisconsin analyzed data from the 60 
largest public school systems between 1967 and 1986 
they concluded the schools have become increasingly segregated 
over that period because of a dramatic rise in hispanic students 
and a steady erosion in white enrollment 
predictions about central city districts losing the majority 
of their white students came true orfield said wednesday but 
now not only are blacks still being segregated hispanics are 
being more segregated at an evenfaster rate 
however the segregation is not the result of whites leaving 
public schools so much as migration patterns and changes in the 
birth rates he added 
among the reports most significant findings 
total enrollment declined by 15 percent in the 60 districts to 
67 million over the 19year period white enrollment declined by 
16 percent while the number of black students increased by 5 
percent and hispanic students by 103 percent 
the 25 largest central city school districts now serve 28 
percent of all black students 30 percent of all hispanics but 
only 3 percent of white students 
what that means he said is that the school systems that 
are decisive to the future of large parts of our minority groups 
are almost irrelevant to the white population 
almost half of the largest public school districts are now in 
the suburbs and metropolitan counties alongside urban centers 
the researchers did not attempt to assess the consequences of 
segregation or to propose solutions 
but orfield said schools that serve black and hispanic 
populations exclusively serve a disproportionate number of poor 
kids they continue to do much worse than white schools in academic 
achievement graduation rates and almost any other measure of 
providing a successful education 
and the worst part he added is that almost nothing 
substantial is being done to change it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

