<TEXT>
police cordoned off burmas holiest 
buddhist shrine at dawn today and surrounded student demonstrators 
who had set up a strike center on its grounds 
the closing of gates leading to the shwedagon pagoda a 
centuriesold hilltop shrine comes after students angered by 
authorities closing of their schools fought riot police in the 
capitals streets 
a dawntodusk curfew was imposed in rangoon after tuesdays 
clashes in which state radio said nine people were killed and 77 
arrested 
following the closure of the rangoon institute of technology 
wednesday morning students from the campus went to the shwedagon 
and opened a strike center the pagodas central tower is 
covered with several tons of gold 
some pilgrims returning from the pagoda wednesday said about 500 
students were on its grounds the figure could not to be confirmed 
and details of what occured in the pagoda after the gates were shut 
were not available 
classes at key schools in burmas second largest city mandalay 
were suspended today and a curfew was imposed wednesday night in 
pegu following mob violence according to residents reached by 
telephone pegu is 55 miles north of rangoon 
the pegu residents said demonstrators destroyed some government 
buildings cooperative shops and vehicles in a rampage that began 
in front of a high school 
residents said there was no unrest in mandalay 385 miles north 
of rangoon and the suspension of classes at mandalay university 
medical college and the government technical institute seemed to be 
preventive measures 
the current protests appear to stem from widespread 
disatisfaction with the oneparty regime of military strongman ne 
win who seized power in a 1962 coup the government has restricted 
individual freedoms and economic conditions in what was once one 
of asias wealthiest nations have worsened in recent years 
most shops in rangoons sprawling markets closed at noon today 
for fear of looting in the event of renewed unrest and some 
government employees left work early 
students dressed in green sarongs the uniform of high school 
students tried unsuccessfully to persuade residents in some parts 
of the city to join them on a march to the heavily guarded pagoda 
the march did not materialize 
the government has also banned all processions demonstrations 
and public meetings the restrictions are to last until aug 19 
attendance at high schools and the education institute the 
capitals only center of higher learning still open was minimal 
teachers have been instructed to continue classes regardless of the 
number of students attending 
no major incidents have been reported in rangoon since the 
curfew was imposed on tuesday a few taxi drivers trishaw 
pedallers and street vendors have been arrested for venturing into 
the streets before curfew ends at 6 am but have reportedly been 
released after a warning 
the disturbances in the capital erupted tuesday when about 5000 
students and other protestors fought stonethrowing duels with 
police 
students at several institutions had peacefully demonstrated 
last week for the release of detained students and legalization of 
student unions violence erupted after the government responded by 
closing the schools 
the countrys first riots since 1974 erupted last october when 
the government declared invalid much of the currency in circulation 
and offered no compensation on march 18 several days of student 
unrest climaxed in a rampage by students and others that was 
swiftly crushed by police and military units 
a government panel announced only two deaths and said 625 people 
were arrested many of them since freed but diplomatic sources 
told reporters in bangkok thailand that as many as 100 people 
died in the march violence 
