<TEXT>
scientists campaigning against nuclear weapons say 
new calculations confirm that about 23 tons of plutonium produced 
in british civil nuclear reactors is missing 
but authorities say the scientists have misunderstood the 
problem and gotten their figures wrong 
in a letter published today in nature a science weekly an 
american and three british scientists say their 1985 claim of a 
shortfall is borne out by more detailed figures which the 
government began publishing last year 
they say they dont know where the missing plutonium has gone 
but speculate that it went to nuclear weapons programs in britain 
or the united states or both 
the letter to nature is signed by physicists keith barnham of 
the imperial college london david hart of the pressure group 
scientists against nuclear arms jenny nelson of bristol 
university and rob stevens of unicam corp aptox calif 
the problem centers on a 68ton gap between government civil 
stockpiles and the amount the scientists calculate actually were 
produced 
the scientists said they have calculated that four tons went to 
the united states in exchange for enriched uranium under an 
agreement that lasted until 1971 
about half a ton was lost in reprocessing leaving 23 tons 
unaccounted for they wrote 
they said their 1985 calculations could not be confirmed because 
the government then was not disclosing figures 
but when the government began publishing figures for each of its 
nine reactors these coincided with the physicists earlier 
calculations proving their original model was correct they wrote 
even so the government figures are rounded out to the nearest 
110 pounds of plutonium per reactor which taken together would be 
enough to arm 100 warheads a year barnham said in an interview 
diane monk a spokeswoman for the governments central 
electricity generating board said the scientists figures are 
inaccurate because large numbers are involved and because they 
would appear to lack basic understanding of the processes 
involved 
</TEXT>
