<TEXT>
next weeks communist party conference may name 
new members to the policysetting central committee but it will 
stick to the old practice of closing the door on most of its 
debates an official said thursday 
yuri a sklyarov of the central committees propaganda 
department said the conference opening tuesday could name new 
members to the 300plus member party body that formulates policy 
and signs off on key personnel changes between the party 
congresses which normally are held every five years 
but he did not say definitely that there would be new members to 
replace socalled dead souls 60 to 70 members who have died 
or lost the jobs that entitled them to central committee seats 
since the last party congress in 1986 
for many months after gorbachev announced in january 1987 that 
he would hold the first party conference since 1941 soviet 
officials and journalists predicted it would make sweeping changes 
in the central committee to give the kremlin leader a body strongly 
backing his reforms 
the strength of conservatives who are braking change appears to 
have scaled down the expectations of a sweeping personnel shakeup 
and radical reforms 
many moscow intellectuals now say they expect the conference to 
be more of a dress rehearsal for a proreform congress in 1991 
saying gorbachev may have learned from this experience how to do to 
avoid conservative maneuvering to dominate delegate slates 
sklyarov said thursday that live television coverage of the 
conference will be limited to a broadcast of the opening session 
where gorbachev will set the tone with a report on the present and 
future pace of reform and a report on the closing session 
delegate speeches will be summarized on tv and printed in full 
in newspapers once the speakers themselves have had a chance to 
approve the text sklyarov said 
the arrangements are almost identical to those for the february 
1986 congress and seem certain to disappoint the most outspoken 
reformers who had demanded live tv coverage of the entire meeting 
as a way of making the communist party more accountable to the 
people it rules 
strengthening political accountability and the legal system are 
two declared goals of the 30page conference proposals known as 
theses which have been fiercely debated in the media and at party 
meetings since being approved by the central committee may 23 
the theses contain proposals that could dismantle the vestiges 
of stalinism but are vaguely worded in a possible attempt to fend 
off conservatives 
sklyarov said hundreds of thousands of suggestions based on the 
theses have poured into the central committee which is collating 
them for presentation to the agendasetting presidium of the 
conference 
he declined to specify however who is collating the proposals 
and exactly how the presidium will be selected 
georgian communist party head dzhumber patiashvili said 
important representatives of each conference delegation will huddle 
after all 5000 arrive in moscow on sunday 
those discussions are likely to remain secret ivan d laptev 
chief editor of the government newspaper izvestia said his daily 
would publish details only if they were interesting 
yegor yakovlev a delegate and editor of the proreform weekly 
moscow news said wednesday about 70 delegates will take the floor 
during the conference which soviet spokesman gennady gerasimov has 
said will last through july 1 
but sklyarov and other officials refused to confirm that 
timetable suggesting the duration and agenda of the conference are 
still open 
patiashvili said the 106member georgian delegation is still 
meeting in his republic to decide its platform at the conference 
he said he had not read the radical platforms published by the 
baltic republics of estonia and latvia which demanded a form of 
home rule georgias demands will not be published as a program he 
said but may contain a few similar proposals for more autonomy 
from moscow 
party congresses theoretically are the supreme organ of the 
party usually meeting every five years to name members of the 
central committee and formulate policy party conferences which 
were held infrequently before 1941 but have not been convened since 
then are convened to take up special proposals 
