<TEXT>
the house on thursday refused to kill a 
proposal barring discrimination in housing for families with 
children 
the house rejected on a vote of 289116 an amendment proposed by 
rep clay shaw rfla that would have stripped the protection for 
families with children from legislation designed to strengthen the 
enforcement of the nations fair housing law 
under the bill families with children under 18 could not be 
refused housing except in retirement communities where at least 90 
percent of the tenants are 55 or older and the facilities are 
specifically designed for the physical or social needs of retirees 
any community renting to those 62 or older would be exempt even if 
it did not provide special facilities 
final action on the bill was delayed as the house recessed for 
the day to attend the funeral services of rep john j duncan 
rtenn in knoxville the bill is expected to be taken up again 
late next week 
senate leaders have said they would take up the bill after the 
house approves it indicating that the legislation may go to the 
white house before the end of summer 
civil rights groups and realtors earlier this week ended a 
20year battle by reaching a compromise to put teeth in the basic 
fairhousing law while still satisfying president reagans concerns 
about constitutional guarantees 
the bill would give the department of housing and urban 
development the power to bring actions on behalf of individual 
victims of discrimination would ban discrimination against the 
disabled and would forbid limitations on renting to families with 
children except in the clearly defined retirement communities 
under the compromise hud would be required to investigate 
complaints of discrimination in the sale or rental of housing and 
it would be authorized to lodge charges if it finds reasonable 
cause to believe that discrimination may have occurred 
at that point there would be an administrative proceeding 
unless either the plaintiff or the defendant requests a jury trial 
either proceeding could lead to imposition of fines or injunctions 
and could be appealed to a higher court 
the compromise language which gives the accused the right to a 
civil trial by jury was introduced by rep hamilton fish jr 
rny and was passed by the house 4010 
the house also passed by voice vote an amendment by rep barney 
frank dmass which would permit the exclusion of an individual 
who threatens the safety of others and one by rep robert s 
walker rpa to take away protection of the law from anyone 
convicted of drug manufacturing 
the shaw amendment would have eliminated the provisions of the 
bill extending protection from housing discrimination to families 
with children under the age of 18 it would have required the civil 
rights commission to conduct a study on the nature and extent of 
housing discrimination against familes with children and report to 
congress within three years 
