members of congress and spokesmen for postal 
workers expressed alarm thursday over the shipment of biological 
toxins and other deadly agents through the us mail system saying 
the items are not properly packaged at times 
but officials from the defense department and the centers for 
disease control both shippers of such items defended their 
procedures and said elaborate packaging precautions are taken 
the postal service said it is considering tighter regulations 
that would ban the shipment of some diseasecausing agents and 
microorganisms from its mail service 
the action is being considered because an expected increase in 
such shipments through the postal service could cause a possible 
hazard to postal workers frank henselton assistant postmaster 
general said at a congressional hearing 
the proposed regulation was to be issued thursday followed by a 
45day comment period before a final rule is taken under 
consideration he said many of the shipments of diseaserelated 
agents already are shipped by private overnight carriers 
the postal services assurances did not ease some of the concern 
expressed by members of a subcommittee of the post office and civil 
service committee 
these viruses are intended for warfare theyre intended to 
kill people declared rep barbara boxer dcalif adding that 
