<TEXT>
the veterans administration announced thursday 
the discovery of 10 million military medical records that duplicate 
some lost in a devastating 1973 fire and said it will review 
disability claims that were rejected because of the lost files 
thomas k turnage the va administrator said the agency just 
became aware of the records last week and it was too early to tell 
how many people would be affected but he called the development 
very important 
it opens up new vistas for us it means that these people who 
before had difficulty establishing a basis for their disability 
compensation or the degree of it it means we can have another 
chance to look at it and in effect may come up with a different 
result turnage said 
john sommer the director of the american legion veterans 
affairs and rehabilitation commission whose office helps veterans 
with their disability claims said the development potentially 
could affect thousands of former military personnel 
weve handled many cases where there were no records because 
of the fire and its very difficult to develop additional evidence 
on which to try to get these claims allowed he said in an 
interview 
youd be amazed at the number of people world war ii veterans 
in particular who waited until they retired to file a claim with 
the va and then found the records had been destroyed sommer 
said many of them felt they just didnt want to take anything 
from the government then as they aged they decided to file a 
claim and discovered their records had been burned 
eighteen million military personnel records were destroyed or 
seriously damaged in the july 12 1973 fire at the national 
personnel record center in st louis mo the lost records were 
from the years 1912 through 1959 for army personnel and 1947 
through 1963 for air force personnel with the surnames of hubbard 
and through the letter z 
the duplicate records cover the years 1942 to 1945 and 1950 to 
1954 so will primarily affect veterans of world war ii and the 
korean war 
the records were collected by the national research council a 
private research organization during the 1950s as part of its 
analysis of army hospital records a researcher at the council came 
across the records and notified the national archives said jill 
brett an archives spokeswoman 
ms brett said the records are on computer magnetic tapes 
created by the council from admissions punch cards prepared by the 
office of the surgeon general she said the archives paid the 
council 8662 for the tapes and will reformat them for 
crossreferencing against other files 
the records were not listed by the military officers name but 
included the officers serial number grade and rank age date and 
place of admission as well as disease and diagnosis ms brett said 
veterans applying for monthly disability benefits as a result of 
injury or illness suffered while on active duty must have some 
verification of their claim turnage said he did not have figures 
on how many disability claims had been denied as a result of the 
lost records 
there were 35 million files that turned up for the year 1944 
alone turnage said covering about 24 million people for 1945 2 
million files were discovered covering about 14 million people 
but officials cautioned against the notion that millions of 
veterans would be affected by the discovery rj vogel the vas 
chief benefits director said that most of the veterans who made 
disability claims did so during their initial years after service 
and likely would have filed claims before 1973 
those most likely to be affected by the discovery of the records 
include people with an injury suffered during active duty which was 
aggravated over the years such as a back or heart ailment vogel 
said 
the va said it would immediately begin reviewing disability 
claims rejected because of the lost records the agency said it 
also expected many veterans would come forward seeking information 
about their claims it said those people should contact their va 
regional offices 
