<TEXT>
us agriculture secretary richard lyng said 
thursday federal programs will provide relief for droughtstricken 
farmers but governors meeting in emergency session questioned 
whether those methods were adequate 
during a brief appearance before the 10 governors who gathered 
for the daylong conference lyng promised the federal government 
will do what is needed to minimize the severity of the damage 
but the agriculture secretary also reminded the gathering that 
there were several existing aid programs already in place and he 
stressed repeatedly that the extent of the damage from the drought 
was yet to be determined 
but gov george sinner of north dakota speaking at a closing 
news conference said farmers in several states already had lost 
much of their cash crops and others have sold off entire livestock 
herds for lack of feed grain 
where i think he lyng is wrong is in the wheat area said 
sinner that damage is done and it is very very severe in the 
livestock feed area that damage is done and its going to grow 
sinner also said government programs must be made flexible 
enough to ensure that farmers hurt by the current drought arent 
disqualified from participating in cropinsurance and disasterloan 
program because of technicalities 
im afraid were going to lose some farmers he said and 
weve lost enough already in my state 
that message echoed throughout the day 
welcome to the heart of the droughtland illinois gov james 
thompson said in opening the conference we used to be known as 
the heart of the heartland now we are both 
in his speech lyng noted that 1200 counties in 30 states 
already have been granted permission for grazing livestock or 
making hay on governmentrented land normally set aside for 
conservation or cropreduction plans 
he also pointed out that task forces already have been set up 
within the administration and congress to study the consequences of 
the drought the federal governments cropinsurance and 
disasterloan programs could serve large number of farmers once the 
extent of the damage from the drought becomes clear he said 
the situation is still fluid well need a little bit of 
time to learn what the losses are he said 
before he left the conference lyng said he would meet with 
reagan on friday morning to update him on the drought situation 
but several governors suggested the situation in their states 
already demands a morespecific response from the federal goverment 
