<DOCNO> AP880623-0237 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
harry cook worries that the 
rolling green countryside of spencers wood is endangered that 
throngs from london 35 miles to the east will pour into tracts of 
houses where now there are trees and meadows 
he heads a group of 450 local residents opposing the 
suburbanization of their countryside in spencers wood and all of 
berkshire county where tiny villages are designated by the 
government as the sites for thousands of new homes for people 
overflowing from crowded london 
the battle of berkshire is a test case in a political 
controversy brewing across southern england where the green belt 
a ring of protected land around london has put housingdevelopment 
pressure on more outlying rural areas like spencers wood 
once the atmosphere goes its no longer country living so to 
speak said cook as he surveyed smokestacks and a sea of 
rowhouses on one side of the highway running through the area and 
the green land on the other 
the issue touches sensitive political nerves 
critics even in prime minister margaret thatchers conservative 
party say that by funneling development to the wealthy southern 
england the government is ignoring the economically ailing north 
and widening national divisions 
environment minister nicholas ridley and developers argue that 
houses must be built where they are needed and thats in the 
south they maintain that denying freemarket forces a cornerstone 
of mrs thatchers policies would dampen southern growth 
this issue is potentially as explosive for the tories 
conservatives as any that has caused rumblings of discontent 
within their ranks during the past decade commented the 
financial times 
at the heart of the controversy is the green belt the 12 
million acres set aside 50 years ago around london to keep the city 
from sprawling to the sea give it a green lung and preserve 
the citys character belts around other cities followed and green 
belts now cover 14 percent of england 
as part of her goal of transforming britain into a 
propertyowning democracy mrs thatcher wants everyone to have 
the chance to buy a home but she could not touch the green belts 
without alienating large numbers of voters in the south her 
electoral heartland 
the planned channel tunnel linking southern england to france 
and the growth of london as a financial capital have sent real 
estate prices soaring and added greater burdens on hospitals and 
other services 
opponents like harry cook say its fine to protect the green 
belts but unfair to make the countryside pay the price they say 
inner cities should be revitalized with new housing 
we think its bad management for britains inner cities to be 
depopulating and green fields to be built over said jerry 
wiggin a lawmaker who opposes his conservative partys development 
policy 
richard bate senior planner for the 60yearold council for the 
protection of rural england cpre says if we continue to have 
major housebuilding and investment in the southeast and not in 
other parts of the country the problem of two nations under one 
government is going to become even greater than it already is 
ridley argues that city dwellers need parks and green spaces 
and gardens too and resent the implication that all development 
can just be dumped in their backyard 
the controversy heated up in february after ridley increased 
estimates of southeast housing needs from 460000 homes to a 
possible 610000 by the year 2000 
weve taken berkshire as a test case because it is the 
county under the greatest pressure the cpres bate said in an 
interview its an area which has seen a doubling of its housing 
stock in the last 30 years where villages have already been 
absorbed into main towns 
a rightwing think tank the adam smith institute has suggested 
reviving green belt land that was once used for industry and fell 
derelict after the conservation area was introduced 
it says up to 40 percent of the belt consists of such brown 
patches and proposes letting developers in provided they also make 
other spoiled areas green again 
harry cook and his neighbors in the meantime worry about what 
they will lose 
small developments already peek from behind the trees and old 
homes of their region 
london already has encroached 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880623-0238 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
after 49 million worth of renovations to 
bring the white house of the confederacy to its civil wartime 
stateliness restorers are welcoming visitors again to the 
executive mansion of another nation 
the house built in 1818 was leased to the confederate 
government for use as the residence of president jefferson davis 
and in it he often mapped war strategy with his generals including 
robert e lee and thomas stonewall jackson 
it gives a glimpse into the life of the souths first family 
while reflecting the decline and death of the confederate states of 
america 
as the war went on the quality of what was served went 
down said david s bundy director of development and public 
relations at the house and the museum of the confederacy next door 
by the end of the civil war he said the white house was 
serving what became known as jefferson davis punch water 
richmond the capital of the confederacy had bought the house 
for 42000 in 1861 
three decades after the war in 1896 it opened as the 
confederate museum but closed in 1976 when its confederate 
collections were moved to the new museum its restoration and 
reopening this month were underwritten by 49 million in private 
corporate state and federal donations 
we feel like the white house is one of the most important 
historical houses in america bundy said it was the executive 
mansion of another nation whether youre from the north or the 
south it played a big part in our destiny 
the threestory classical revivalstyle white house actually 
painted a pale gray stands in the heart of the citys historic 
court end district 
visitors can tread on a recreation of the white carpet on which 
lee inadvertently tracked mud restorers learned the carpet was 
white from a reference davis wife varina made to the incident 
general lee came up from camp one day evidently worn out and 
worried to find mr davis lying quite ill on a divan in a little 
morningroom in which we received only our intimate friends mrs 
davis recalled in her memoirs general lee with a bow and excuse 
for coming in on the white carpet with his splashed boots sat down 
and plunged at once into army matters 
visitors also can see the secondfloor office where davis met 
with lee and jackson to discuss strategy and the front parlor where 
davis entertained the public bundy said 
authenticity was important to those restoring the house the 
only nonperiod pieces in sight are smoke alarms 
most of the furniture in the house was used by the davises in 
the four years they lived there and was donated to the restoration 
effort a painted floor cloth in the round entranceway was very 
trendy at the time 
anything thats not a davis piece is of the period bundy 
said 
most of the gaslight chandeliers in the house are original and 
have been restored we could have used substitutes and 99 
percent of the public never would have known he said 
restorers analyzed the paint on the furniture to determine which 
coat was on top when davis lived in the house 
reproducing textiles throughout the house cost quite a bit 
over 100000 bundy said 
a new york textile reproduction company created a green and gold 
silk for the drapes and an ottoman in the dining room that is 
almost identical to the fabric in place 123 years ago 
we have these original fabrics these are pieces of history 
if we can recreate them we make every effort bundy said 
it was painstaking work copying the original design on graph 
paper dying yarn to match the original colors and handtying 
15000 threads individually to a loom said adriana bitter one of 
the owners of scalamandre a restoration consultant in new york 
city 
the silk left the loom at a rate of only 4 yards in an 8hour 
workday she said the pattern still is not an exact copy because 
the patterns in the new fabric do not repeat at the same rate mrs 
bitter said it could have been done for another 30000 
restorers discovered the house had one more room than previously 
thought a secretarys office adjacent to davis they found a 
joint that indicated where a wall had once been 
among furniture and other items that davis and his family used 
are his office chair and desk 
many other items left in the pockets of northern soldiers while 
the house was being used as union army headquarters after the war 
a lot of union officers took souvenirs from the house and a 
lot of them have found their way back bundy said many were 
returned when the museum first opened in the house at the turn of 
the century others such as spurs davis wore have come back 
within the last month 
</TEXT>
