norway will restrain by 75 percent its 
north sea oil production during the second half of 1988 the oil 
and energy ministry announced thursday 
ministry spokesman egil helle said the restrained level will 
mean a daily production of 90000 barrels below full capacity but 
new wells and fields will be opened during the next six months 
raising norways overall production helle said 
the cut will apply to all offshore fields 
the energy ministry said that norways average daily production 
during the first half of 1988 was about 1035 billion barrels 
during the second half it is projected to reach 1125 billion 
barrels 
norway is not a member of the organization of petroleum 
exporting countries but it has held back on production since 
february 1986 in line with opecs efforts to stabilize prices 
the governments decision to reduce the production growth is a 
contribution to stabilization of oil prices the ministry said 
