italian financier carlo de benedetti 
has agreed to sharply reduce his stake in societe generale de 
belgique ending a lengthy takeover battle for belgiums largest 
holding company sources said thursday 
under terms of a settlement de benedetti will sell part of his 
45 percent stake in societe generale to cie financiere de suez a 
french banking company that along with its allies holds a slim 
majority 
the sale will reduce de benedettis holdings to about 15 
percent thereby blocking his ability to manipulate decisions that 
require a 75 percent vote of shareholders 
in return however de benedetti would get a cash payment at 
least three seats on societe generales board and would increase 
his stake in suez according to sources who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
the agreement is expected to be formally announced friday at a 
news conference called by societe generale whose holdings in 
industries including energy finance chemicals mining and 
transport control about a third of belgiums economy 
de benedetti announced in january he sought to control societe 
generale the belgian company resisted his overtures but had to 
look for foreign support in suez which along with the belgian 
insurer groupe ag came to control slightly more than 50 percent of 
the holdign companys shares 
at a special meeting two months ago shareholders spurned de 
benedettis bid to win board seats for himself and two allies 
suezs strengthened stake under the settlement should allow the 
french group to run societe generale with its own new chief 
executive reorganizing the companys often criticized strategy as 
well as its management structure 
a statement issued earlier this week confirming negotiations 
were underway said suez and its allies will back the nomination of 
herve de carmoy a french banker to societe generales board 
while de benedetti and his allies will abstain 
it is expected that de carmoy will be asked to take over a large 
part of societe generales management 
the frenchbelgian group was also reported to be interested in 
looking for more foreign partners including the british media 
magnate robert maxwell 
