he spoke at the end of the daylong seminar in this southern 
dutch town on the future of the airline industry in the 
deregulated liberalized common market envisioned after 1992 
the conference convened by dutch transport minister neelie 
smitkroes drew 40 representatives from common market airlines 
civil aviation authorities and governments 
the european economic community has a 1992 goal of removing all 
trade barriers among its members including western europes 
patchwork of bilateral aviation agreements 
although some nations notably britain and the netherlands 
already have liberalized aviation agreements most european 
countries severely limit the freedom of operation for foreign 
airlines 
after 1992 european airlines would be free to choose their 
destinations and flight frequencies experts at the seminar 
predicted that only a few very large carriers will be able to 
survive 
seminar participants heard a report by the international 
foundation of airline passenger associations on possible effects of 
european airline mergers on the flying public the dutch transport 
ministry commissioned the report by the private genevabased 
organization 
in the report ifapas executive director geoffrey lipman said 
eec members should maintain some regulations to safeguard airline 
passengers he said that after the 1978 deregulation of civil 
aviation in the united states passenger complaints on congestion 
delays and bad service mushroomed 
raben said that while the us government abolished many of the 
regulations affecting the airline industry in one move were 
planning a gradual change in europe 
