<TEXT>
all three measures of the nations money supply 
tumbled in midjune the federal reserve board reported thursday 
the fed said its narrowest measure of the money supply m1 fell 
21 billion in the week ended june 13 to a seasonally adjusted 
7718 billion from 7739 billion the previous week 
it said the measure known as m2 fell 48 billion to a 
seasonally adjusted 3013 billion from 3018 billion 
an even broader measure m3 fell 18 billion to a seasonally 
adjusted 3794 billion from 3796 billion 
m1 includes cash in circulation deposits in checking accounts 
and nonbank travelers checks m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings 
deposits and moneymarket mutual funds m3 is m2 plus lessliquid 
accounts such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations 
of 100000 
the central bank considers the two broader measures of the money 
supply as well as the value of the dollar commodity prices and the 
difference between short and longterm interest rates in setting 
its monetary policy 
but most economists say that recent movements in the money 
supply do not appear to have played a very significant role in 
those deliberations 
in other reports thursday 
the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and 
industrial loans at major new york city banks rose 952 million in 
the week ended june 15 compared with a gain of 133 million the 
previous week 
